I always struggle with flow practices-- I try to go too quick or I try to force my breath to match the movement instead of following my breath to make the movement, etc. etc.,, but after that pause in the middle I felt so much more connected. I struggled to make my mat a sacred space today. I was tired and annoyed and thoughts I was trying to put down kept popping up in my mind. BUT I DID IT! I got through the most challenging day yet and I am proud of myself. My breath feels more confident now, and I am more willing to listen to it and let it guide me. Happy that I made it and am so proud of everyone else who did as well. Reading comments is always wonderful, but today they were surprisingly more meaningful. Yay!

Todays session helped me realize I tend to flow with other peoples expectations, rather than my own breath and limits. While I always feel great when I nail the poses, the truth is my muscles aren‚Äôt quite strong enough to hold me with stability in some of them, and it would be so much more loving to flow with what‚Äôs actually here in todays practice. The point of yoga is the juicy stuff along the way, not nailing the final pose!! I have the rest of my life to do just that ü•≤ I won‚Äôt be a beginner forever, and I‚Äôll savor every moment. I think this way it just takes the expectation off of being perfect, and we can celebrate every step we take on this journey üíó

Does anyone know what the movement is called where you sit cross-legged and inhale with your hands lifting to the heart, exhale hands moving to prayer, retain the breath as you bow, inhale arms raised and exhale to lower to the earth? 

I have done it before on Adrienes other videos and had an amazing experience today. As I inhaled from hands to the earth, I focused all of my energy from root to sacral to solar plexus and paused at the heart (which is the center of all chakras), then the next inhale I moved up from throat to third eye to crown and exhaled focusing from crown to root back the opposite way. Usually I have trouble focusing on the present waiting for my hands to touch eachother or the ground, but after focusing on the energy centers, pausing at the heart and moving back up to the crown then back down again, I rediscovered a new way to move through that motion. I hope this helps anyone who have also struggled focusing the mind when moving through those motions. Thank you Adriene!

To be completely honest with you, Adriene, although I truly love your practices I have to force myself onto the mat sometimes. 
My brain finds new ways trying to convince me not to do something that I know is actually good for me.
"No, this is boring / exhausting, you will sweat, you will be tired afterwards, you will be sore, you will be out of breath and so on."

In september this year, I found my daily life change completely as my panic attacks and anxiety left me unable to work or leave the house. I had to learn how to even take walks again, as any type of movement that ups the heart rate or tires my body past a certain level triggers my fight or flight. But I started doing yoga with adriene from mid September on a near daily basis and allthough slow, I can see so much progress. Before september I worked out 3 days a week and was in a physically demanding job and so I was always on the go. But I felt I was just moving without purpose, and moving without stopping to rest and notice what was manifesting inside. For the last 3 months I hardly move and I've noticed the massive decline in my strength and endurance. This 30 day journey allthough extremely tough mentally (and physically) at some points, feels like exactly what I need to wake up  and ( more importantly) feel safe in my body again. I'm so thankful for this xx
